{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480652"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:48:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:48:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"90"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"90","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/90"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.14,0.15,0.02,0.65]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"90"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106984"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"90","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/90"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"90"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89447"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"99"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"1693"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3724"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14531"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41986"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106984"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 59-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of sudden onset central chest pain that began while he was at rest. He has a medical history of angina and hypertension. His regular medications include aspirin, atorvastatin, amlodipine and glyceryl trinitrate spray PRN. On this occasion, the pain was not relieved by his glyceryl trinitrate spray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 130/min, blood pressure 80/55 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. His jugular venous pressure is elevated, and a new systolic murmur is heard on chest auscultation. His pulse is weak and thready. There are bibasal crackles on lung auscultation. An ECG is obtained (Image). Troponin T is elevated at 2500 ng/L (0-14).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aortic regurgitation","Aortic stenosis","Left ventricular aneurysm","Ventricular tachycardia","Papillary muscle rupture"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of an acute anterolateral myocardial infarction (MI) complicated by cardiogenic shock and acute mitral regurgitation. The sudden onset of dyspnoea, hypotension, and a new systolic murmur in the setting of an acute MI strongly suggests a mechanical complication, most likely \u003Cstrong\u003Epapillary muscle rupture\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E is an unlikely complication of MI. It typically presents with a diastolic murmur, which is not described in this case. Moreover, acute aortic regurgitation is more commonly associated with aortic dissection or infective endocarditis rather than MI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic condition that would have been present before the acute event. It does not develop acutely as a complication of MI. Additionally, aortic stenosis typically causes a harsh, crescendo-decrescendo systolic murmur, best heard at the right upper sternal border, which is different from the murmur described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft ventricular aneurysm\u003C/strong\u003E is a subacute to chronic complication of MI, typically developing over weeks to months. It would not explain the acute presentation with shock and a new murmur. Left ventricular aneurysms are also not typically associated with a specific murmur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentricular tachycardia\u003C/strong\u003E, while a possible complication of acute MI, would not explain the new systolic murmur. The stem describes a regular tachycardia of 130/min, which is more consistent with sinus tachycardia than ventricular tachycardia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPapillary muscle rupture most commonly affects the posteromedial papillary muscle due to its single blood supply from the right coronary or circumflex artery. This complication leads to acute, severe mitral regurgitation, resulting in pulmonary oedema and cardiogenic shock. The new systolic murmur, along with signs of acute heart failure and shock in the context of an inferior MI, makes papillary muscle rupture the most likely diagnosis in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute mitral regurgitation due to papillary muscle rupture is a life-threatening mechanical complication of myocardial infarction, presenting with sudden onset of dyspnoea, hypotension, and a new systolic murmur.","Papillary muscle rupture can occur with myocardial infarction, most commonly affecting the posteromedial papillary muscle due to its single blood supply."],"references":["Durko AP, Budde RPJ, Geleijnse ML, Kappetein AP. Recognition, assessment and management of the mechanical complications of acute myocardial infarction. Heart. 2018 Jul;104(14):1216-1223. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29146624/","Montrief T, Davis WT, Koyfman A, Long B. Mechanical, inflammatory, and embolic complications of myocardial infarction: An emergency medicine review. Am J Emerg Med. 2019 Jun;37(6):1175-1183. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30987913/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89447"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"90"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17485"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17485"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e43bc53e-81bc-44a5-81e6-6e23ef9efe7a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e43bc53e-81bc-44a5-81e6-6e23ef9efe7a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1425,"height":715}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89447"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-24T11:52:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-24T11:52:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"90"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106984"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","lin